sec.p:
The genera Caecijaera Menzies, 1951
and Janiralata Menzies, 1951
are members of the isopod family Janiridae G.O. Sars, 1897 , which includes approximately 150 species in 23 genera ( Wilson 1994 ;
Boyko et al . 2008
;
Linse et al . 2014
). The genus Caecijaera was erected with the type species Caecijaera horvathi Menzies, 1951
collected from California, Northeast Pacific, based on the following diagnostic characteristics: (1) the eyes are absent; (2) the mandibular molar process is greatly reduced and similar to incisor in size; (3) the maxillula has a wide and flattened inner lobe; (4) each of the pereopods has two claws; and (5) the distal end of the pleopod Ⅰ is not expanded laterally (Menzies, 1951). Thereafter, five species have been reported worldwide: Caecijaera borealisKussakin, 1962 from the Barents Sea, Caecijaera derjuginiKussakin, 1962 from the East Sea, Caecijaera mirabilisKussakin, 1962 from the Sea of Okhotsk, Caecijaera cojimarensis Ortiz, 1993
from the Caribbean Sea, and Caecijaera kussakiniMalyutina, 1994 from the South China Sea ( Kussakin 1962 ; Malyutina 1994 ; Ortiz 2020 ).

Until now, these two genera have been reported only from the northern hemisphere, despite the family Janiridae having a worldwide distribution in all the oceans ( Wilson 1994 ;
Boyko et al . 2008
;
Linse et al . 2014
). Caecijaera and Janiralata ’s current distribution and regional specie richness would be caused by the regionally limited taxonomic effort of a few productive taxonomists ( Menzies 1951a ; Kussakin 1962 ; Cooke 1977 ; Svavarsson 1982 ; Wilson & Wägele 1994). Many Janiralata species
also show limited geographical distributions within the North Pacific, in particular, 26 species among the 32 known species have been recorded from the Northwest Pacific ( Krøyer 1847 ; Thielemann 1910 ; Gurjanova 1933 ; Kussakin 1962 , 1972 , 1988 ; Birstein 1970 ; Jang 1991 ; Wilson & Wägele 1994; Shimonura 2006). So far, one Caecijaera and four Janiralata species
have been reported from the surrounding waters of Korea in the Northwest Pacific (
): C . derjuginiKussakin, 1962 from Russia ; J . chuni ( Thielemann, 1910 )
from Japan ; J . koreaensisJang, 1991 from Korea ; J . sagamiensis Shimonura, 2006
from Japan and Korea ; J . shiinoiKussakin, 1962 from the East China Sea ( Thielemann 1910 ; Kussakin 1962 ; Jang 1991 ; Shimomura 2006 ; Kim & Yoon 2021 ).

